<TITLE> Rice talks with India resume Sunday </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, March 29 (bdnews24.com)The second round of talks between Bangladesh and India on fixing the prices and schedule of importing four lakh tonnes of rice from India is set to resume Sunday, a senior official of the Food Directorate said. The meeting was suspended Thursday without any decision, director of the Food Directorate Elahi Dad Khan told reporters . The two sides will resume the meeting Sunday to reach a final decision. If the decision is finalised, an agreement will be signed with Indian exporters, Khan said Thursday. The first two meetings were held on March 17-18, with a third starting after a 12-day pause. Director general of the Food Directorate Pius Costa led the Bangladesh team that included directors Elahi Dad Khan, Siddiqur Rahman and Abdul Halim. The Indian team of four rice exporting firms was led by TPS Narayan. After the meeting, Khan said, the time schedule is being given more importance over prices for import of four lakh tonnes out of the five lakh tonnes earlier pledged by India. The Indian delegates have agreed to release the shipments within 60 days instead of 90 days from agreement. Bangladesh has asked them to give the shipments within 45 days. Khan also said: "We are importing rice for distribution, not for sale." bdnews24.
